  "prompt": "What's the difference between scattering and diffraction?",
  "response": "Both scattering and diffraction are wave phenomena involving the interaction of waves with obstacles or apertures, but they have some key differences:\n\nScattering:\n- Occurs when waves interact with particles or objects much smaller than their wavelength\n- Waves are redirected in multiple directions\n- No specific pattern is usually formed\n- Depends on the size and composition of scattering objects\n- Examples: Light scattering by molecules, Rayleigh scattering in the atmosphere\n\nDiffraction:\n- Occurs when waves pass through an opening or around an obstacle comparable to their wavelength\n- Creates an interference pattern with distinct bright and dark regions\n- Produces predictable, systematic wave behavior\n- Depends on the wavelength and size of the aperture or obstacle\n- Examples: Light passing through a narrow slit, sound waves around barriers\n\nIn summary:\n- Scattering is more random and less structured\n- Diffraction involves systematic wave interference and pattern formation\n- The key difference lies in the relative size of the wavelength compared to the obstacle or opening",
